{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600777"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:07:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15633"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15633"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.03,0.69,0.19,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8324"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66475"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8324"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51928"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5295"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"},{"type":"tags","id":"10132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22240"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66475"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECushing syndrome is characterised by excessive glucocorticoid levels in the body. In Cushing disease, a pituitary adenoma produces excessive amounts of adrenocorticotrophic hormone, which in turn, stimulate excessive glucocorticoid production and secretion from the adrenal glands.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following layers of the gland is the primary site of cortisol production?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Capsule","Medulla","Zona fasciculata","Zona glomerulosa","Zona reticularis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe adrenal gland consists of distinct anatomical and functional layers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezona fasciculata\u003C/strong\u003E is the middle and thickest layer of the adrenal cortex, responsible for producing glucocorticoids (mainly cortisol)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedulla\u003C/strong\u003E produces catecholamines (adrenaline and noradrenaline)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezona glomerulosa\u003C/strong\u003E is the outermost layer of the cortex and produces mineralocorticoids (aldosterone)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecapsule\u003C/strong\u003E is the outer fibrous layer that provides structural support\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezona reticularis\u003C/strong\u003E is the innermost layer of the cortex and produces androgens\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Cushing syndrome, there is excess cortisol production, which primarily occurs in the zona fasciculata.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cortisol is produced primarily in the zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex.","The three zones of the adrenal cortex each produce different steroid hormones: mineralocorticoids (glomerulosa), glucocorticoids (fasciculata), and androgens (reticularis)."],"references":["Lotfi CFP, Kremer JL, Dos Santos Passaia B, Cavalcante IP. The human adrenal cortex: growth control and disorders. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Sep 6;73(suppl 1):e473s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e473s. PMID: 30208164; PMCID: PMC6113920","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51928"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15633"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51928"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T15:56:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T15:57:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8324"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66475"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data"